ol.li:
If the word is a compound (like "T-shirt"), and you want to keep it on the same line, you
        have two options:

Wrap it in an inline element with the outputclass attribute set. In
						the CSS, change its style to white-space:nowrap;. For
						example:.. <ph outputclass="no-hyphenation">T-shirt</ph>...*[outputclass ~= "no-hyphenation"] {
	white-space: nowrap;
}

A better alternative to this is to write an XSLT extension that matches the text nodes
						and performs an automatic replacement. Please see the example  from
							. Then match the compound-word class like in
						the example
						above:*[outputclass ~= "compound-word"] {
	white-space: nowrap;
}

Another alternative: in all the compound words from your documentation, replace the
						hyphen ("-") with a non-breaking hyphen character U+2011 (or XML
						notation &#2011;). 
Then change the auto-correct settings from
							your editor to automatically replace the compound word with its equivalent. For
							example: "T-shirt" would be replaced with "T[\u2011]shirt".
